text: NASA Space Note number 82-1. 60 seconds, coming in three, two, one. This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. One of the areas that we stand to benefit most from spaceflight is the ability to make scientific observations of the earth from space. On the next space shuttle mission scheduled for October, the orbiter will become an Earth observatory and the astronauts will be gathering geologic, geographic and oceanographic information about our planet. One of the most interesting experiments onboard is the shuttle imaging radar. First flown on the second space shuttle mission, the radar penetrated the arid sands of Sahara to find 60,000 year-old river channels. On this mission, scheduled for October, astronaut Kathy Sullivan will become the first woman to conduct a spacewalk. Together with Commander Dave Leestma, she'll be demonstrating the capability of refueling satellites in space. This has been a NASA Space Note. NASA Space Note number 82-2, 60 seconds, coming in three, two, one. This is a NASA space note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. In an intricate set of maneuvers in space, three satellites from three different nations will create artificial clouds and an imitation comet to study the interaction between the solar wind and the Earth's magnetic field. The solar wind is made up of hot, electrically charged particles that constantly rush outward from the sun's surface. Scientists want to know where these particles enter the magnetic field and how they are circulated and elevated to tremendous energies and whether they are the source of the Van Allen Radiation Belts. The three satellites, called Active Magnetospheric Particle Tracer Explorers, or AMTPTE, one from Germany, one from England and another from NASA, will work together gathering measurements that an international team of scientists hope will provide a flow of valuable new information. This has been a NASA space note. NASA space note number 82-3. 60 seconds, coming in 3, 2, 1. This is a NASA space note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. In ancient Greece, Spartan soldiers carried only the barest essentials with them to do their jobs, yet they performed with efficiency. NASA now applies the same approach to scientific investigations with the Spartan program, which follows the same fundamental philosophy as the sounding rocket program. The satellites are simple and cost-effective. Each Spartan is an autonomous satellite deployed from and retrieved by the space shuttle. Three SPARTAN missions are currently under development. SPARTAN 1 will study clusters of galaxies emitting energy in the form of x-rays, SPARTAN 2 solar physics phenomena, and SPARTAN 3 ultraviolet astronomy. SPARTAN, a simple, reusable, and low-cost tool for investigating a range of scientific problems from atmospheric dynamics to perplexing mysteries of the cosmos. This has been a NASA Space Note. NASA Spacenote number 82-4. 60 seconds, coming in 3, 2, 1. This is a NASA Spacenote from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. Gamma rays are the most energetic form of radiation known. They offer insight into the violent aspects of the space medium and how these processes influence such puzzling objects as pulsars, quasars, black holes, and the ultra bright stars called supernovae. To investigate this area of cosmic radiation, NASA is developing, jointly with Germany, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom, a spacecraft called the Gamma Ray Observatory to be launched in 1988. The observatory, which is managed by NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center, will give scientists an opportunity to study a broad range of cosmic phenomena, such as the origins of extremely high energy bursts, the nuclear processes occurring near neutron stars and black holes, and the nature of recently discovered gamma ray sources in our own Milky Way galaxy. This has been a NASA space note. NASA space note number 82-5. 60 seconds coming in 3, 2, Two. One. This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. Approximately every seventy-six years, the world's most famous Comet sweeps past the Earth, becoming the focus of attention for amateur and professional astronomers. When Comet Halley returns again in the winter of 85 and 86, it will be intensively studied from the ground, air and space. NASA's International Halley Watch was established to coordinate activities of ground based astronomers around the world and to compile the Halley Archives, which will be the largest collection of information ever assembled on a comet. Other observations will include a space shuttle based astro observatory consisting of specially designed ultraviolet telescopes and wide-field cameras, and an unmanned satellite deployed by the shuttle called SPARTAN. Existing NASA satellites, including solar max, will also be reoriented to take a look at Halley. This has been a NASA Space Note. NASA Space Note number 82-6. 60 seconds coming in 3, 2, 1.ש This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. For many years, astronomers learned about the universe by looking at it in the narrow part of the electromagnetic spectrum called visible light. Later they discovered that stars send out kinds of energy that we cannot see, such as infrared and ultraviolet radiation, radio waves, x-rays, and gamma rays. Each part of the spectrum offers a different set of clues to the origin and evolution of the universe. A certain wavelength range, which has never had an astronomical survey, is called the Extreme Ultraviolet Region. Objects in this range are generally stars in highly advanced stages of their evolution. NASA's Extreme Ultraviolet Explorer, scheduled to be launched in 1987, will make an all-sky survey of the Extreme Ultraviolet Range. Observation of a large number of mature stars is expected to provide better understanding of star evolution. This has been a NASA Space Note. NASA Space Note number 82-7, 60 seconds, coming in 3, 2, 1. This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. In a dramatic rescue mission this November, the Space Shuttle Discovery will try to recover at least one of the two communication satellites lost in space last February. The satellites were placed in useless orbits 644 miles high when their onboard rocket engines misfired. The satellites were supposed to reach geosynchronous orbit 22,335 miles above Earth in orbits which would allow them to fly continuously over the same spot. In the rescue mission, commands would be sent to the satellites to drop to a 200-mile-high orbit. Their spin would be slowed from 40 revolutions to 1 a minute. An astronaut wearing a jet-powered backpack would then rendezvous with the satellite and position it so it could be pulled by the shuttle's robot arm into the cargo bay, where it would be returned back to Earth. This has been a NASA space note. NASA space note number 82-8. 60 seconds coming in three, two, one. This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. For 25 years, the American space program has been a stimulus for young people to set their goals high and to strive for excellence. Although in the past, participation of the public in the exciting moonwalks and space shuttle missions has been through real-time television coverage, NASA's spaceflight participation program will now allow ordinary citizens to actually fly on the space shuttle. President Reagan recently announced that an elementary or secondary school teacher would be chosen as the first citizen to fly into space aboard the shuttle. The decision was made because the teachers ability to effectively communicate their knowledge to large groups of students would allow them to inspire young people to become interested in space, science, in mathematics. The person chosen to go will be required to spend a year after the flight talking about his or her experiences to the nation's school children. This has been a NASA Space Note. NASA Space Note number 82-9, 60 seconds coming in three, two, one. This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. In 1978, NASA launched CSAT, an imaging satellite designed to collect data on changing conditions in the world's oceans. CSAT operated only three months, but produced volumes of data, and confirmed that satellites can provide valuable information that is useful in practical applications as well as in scientific studies. NASA is now planning a highly advanced successor to SEASat, a satellite that would provide a vastly improved capability for observing the oceans on a global basis. The Ocean Topography Experiment or Topex, will make radar measurements over the entire ocean basins for several years providing information that will offer practical benefits in such areas as weather prediction, coastal storm warning, maritime safety, waste disposal, ship design, ship routing, and food production from ocean sources. This has been a NASA Space Note. NASA Space Note number 82-10. 60 seconds coming in three two one. This is a NASA Space Note from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. An exciting discovery was recently made at NASA's Ames Research Center in California. The simplest version ever seen of one of life's basic enzymes was found in a salt-loving bacterium. Until now only one form of this energy producing enzyme was known to exist in all living systems. Researchers believe that the newly discovered enzyme maybe left over from early evolution and hope it will provide a model for how early cells function. evolution. The discovery was made by NASA researcher Larry Hochstein. According to Hochstein, the enzyme must have had an early origin in evolution, since it performs an essential function and is found in all living creatures. The fact that only a very complex form of this enzyme exists in present living systems led the Ames Group to search for evidence of a simpler, earlier version. This has been a NASA Space Note. .
